[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The description "Polish" refers to the nationality of logician Jan Łukasiewicz, who invented Polish notation in 1924.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The first computer to use postfix notation, though it long remained essentially unknown outside of Germany, was Konrad Zuse's Z3 in 1941 as well as his Z4 in 1945.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The reverse Polish scheme was again proposed in 1954 by Arthur Burks, Don Warren, and Jesse Wright and was independently reinvented by Friedrich L.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Dijkstra in the early 1960s to reduce computer memory access and use the stack to evaluate expressions.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The algorithms and notation for this scheme were extended by the philosopher and computer scientist Charles L.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] During the 1970s and 1980s, Hewlett-Packard used RPN in all of their desktop and hand-held calculators, and has continued to use it in some models into the 2020s.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In computer science, reverse Polish notation is used in stack-oriented programming languages such as Forth, dc, Factor, STOIC, PostScript, RPL, and Joy.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In reverse Polish notation, the operators follow their operands.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] For example, to add 3 and 4 together, the expression is 3 4 + rather than 3 + 4.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The conventional notation expression 3 − 4 + 5 becomes 3 (enter) 4 − 5 + in reverse Polish notation: 4 is first subtracted from 3, then 5 is added to it.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The concept of a *stack*, a last-in/first-out construct, is integral to the left-to-right evaluation of RPN.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In the example 3 4 −, first the 3 is put onto the stack, then the 4; the 4 is now on top and the 3 below it.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The subtraction operator removes the top two items from the stack, performs 3 − 4, and puts the result of −1 onto the stack.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Common language in this context refers to items being pushed onto the stack when added and popped or removed from the stack when taken off.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The advantage of reverse Polish notation is that it removes the need for order of operations and parentheses that are required by infix notation and can be evaluated linearly, left-to-right.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] For example, the infix expression (3 + 4) × (5 + 6) becomes 3 4 + 5 6 + × in reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Reverse Polish notation has been compared to how one had to work through problems with a slide rule.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In comparison, testing of reverse Polish notation with algebraic notation, reverse Polish has been found to lead to faster calculations, for two reasons.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The first reason is that reverse Polish calculators do not need expressions to be parenthesized, so fewer operations need to be entered to perform typical calculations.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Additionally, users of reverse Polish calculators made fewer mistakes than for other types of calculators.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Later research clarified that the increased speed from reverse Polish notation may be attributed to the smaller number of keystrokes needed to enter this notation, rather than to a smaller cognitive load on its users.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] However, anecdotal evidence suggests that reverse Polish notation is more difficult for users who previously learned algebraic notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Dijkstra invented the shunting-yard algorithm to convert infix expressions to postfix expressions (reverse Polish notation), so named because its operation resembles that of a railroad shunting yard.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] There are other ways of producing postfix expressions from infix expressions.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Most operator-precedence parsers can be modified to produce postfix expressions; in particular, once an abstract syntax tree has been constructed, the corresponding postfix expression is given by a simple post-order traversal of that tree.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The first computer implementing a form of reverse Polish notation (but without the name and also without a stack), was Konrad Zuse's Z3, which he started to construct in 1938 and demonstrated publicly on 12 May 1941.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In dialog mode, it allowed operators to enter two operands followed by the desired operation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] It was destroyed on 21 December 1943 in a bombing raid.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] With Zuse's help a first replica was built in 1961.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The KDF9 designers drew ideas from Hamblin's GEORGE (General Order Generator), a high-level programming language written for a DEUCE computer installed at The New South Wales University of Technology, Kensington, Australia, in 1957.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] One of the designers of the B5000, Robert S.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Friden introduced reverse Polish notation to the desktop calculator market with the EC-130, designed by Robert "Bob" Appleby Ragen, supporting a four-level stack in June 1963.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The successor EC-132 added a square root function in April 1965.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Around 1966, the Monroe Epic calculator supported an unnamed input scheme resembling RPN as well.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] This calculator popularized reverse Polish notation among the scientific and engineering communities.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The HP-35, the world's first handheld scientific calculator, introduced the classical *four-level RPN* with its specific ruleset of the so-called *operational (memory) stack* (later also called *automatic memory stack*) in 1972.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] HP used reverse Polish notation on every handheld calculator it sold, whether scientific, financial, or programmable, until it introduced the HP-10 adding machine calculator in 1977.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] By this time, HP was the leading manufacturer of calculators for professionals, including engineers and accountants.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Later calculators with LCDs in the early 1980s, such as the HP-10C, HP-11C, HP-15C, HP-16C, and the financial HP-12C calculator also used reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In 1988, Hewlett-Packard introduced a business calculator, the HP-19B, without reverse Polish notation, but its 1990 successor, the HP-19BII, gave users the option of using algebraic or reverse Polish notation again.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In 1986, HP introduced RPL, an object-oriented successor to reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The system would display an error message when running out of memory instead of just dropping values off the stack on overflow as with fixed-sized stacks.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] From 1990 to 2003, HP manufactured the HP-48 series of graphing RPL calculators, followed by the HP-49 series between 1999 and 2008.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The last RPL calculator was named HP 50g, introduced in 2006 and discontinued in 2015.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] However, there are several community efforts like newRPL or DB48X to recreate RPL on modern calculators.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] As of 2011, Hewlett-Packard was offering the calculator models 12C, 12C Platinum, 17bII+, 20b, 30b, 33s, 35s, 48gII (RPL) and 50g (RPL) which support reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] While calculators emulating classical models continued to support classical reverse Polish notation, new reverse Polish notation models feature a variant of reverse Polish notation, where the Enter ↑ key behaves as in RPL.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] This latter variant is sometimes known as *entry RPN*.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In 2013, the HP Prime introduced a *128-level* form of entry RPN called *advanced RPN*.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In contrast to RPL with its dynamic stack, it just drops values off the stack on overflow like other fixed-sized stacks do.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] However, like RPL, it does not emulate the behaviour of a classical operational RPN stack to duplicate the top register on drops.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In late 2017, the list of active models supporting reverse Polish notation included only the 12C, 12C Platinum, 17bii+, 35s, and Prime.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] By July 2023, only the 12C, 12C Platinum, the HP 15C Collector's Edition, and the Prime remain active models supporting RPN.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In Britain, Clive Sinclair's Sinclair Scientific (1974) and Scientific Programmable (1975) models used reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In 1974, Commodore produced the Minuteman *6 (MM6) without an Enter ↑ key and the Minuteman *6X (MM6X) with an Enter ↑ key, both implementing a form of *two-level RPN*.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The SR4921 RPN came with a variant of *four-level RPN* with stack levels named X, Y, Z, and W (rather than T) and an Ent key (for "entry").
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] In contrast to Hewlett-Packard's reverse Polish notation implementation, W filled with 0 instead of its contents being duplicated on stack drops.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Among these was the PROGRAM Programmable Scientific Calculator which featured reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The Aircraft Navigation Computer Heathkit OC-1401/OCW-1401 used *five-level RPN* in 1978.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Soviet programmable calculators (MK-52, MK-61, B3-34 and earlier B3-21 models) used reverse Polish notation for both automatic mode and programming.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Modern Russian calculators MK-161 and MK-152, designed and manufactured in Novosibirsk since 2007 and offered by Semico, are backwards compatible with them.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Their extended architecture is also based on reverse Polish notation.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] An eight-level stack was suggested by John A.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] The latter three variants can also be switched between *classical* and *entry RPN* behaviour of the Enter ↑ key, a feature often requested by the community.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] They also support a rarely seen significant figures mode, which had already been available as a compile-time option for the WP 34S and WP 31S.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] Since 2021, the HP-42S simulator Free42 version 3 can be enabled to support a dynamic RPN stack only limited by the amount of available memory instead of the classical 4-level stack.
[src:forth-lang/reverse-polish-notation] This feature was incorporated as a selectable function into the DM42 since firmware DMCP-3.21 / DM42-3.18.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Stack-based algorithms manipulate data by popping data from and pushing data to the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Operators govern how the stack manipulates data.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] To emphasize the effect of a statement, a comment is often used showing the top of the stack before and after the statement; this is known as the stack effect diagram.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Some stack-oriented languages may use multiple stacks for different purposes; for example, PostScript uses separate stacks for variables, dictionaries, procedures, some typical procedures, and control flow statements.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Analysis of the language model allows expressions and programs to be interpreted simply.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] PostScript is an example of a postfix stack-based language.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] An expression example in this language is `2 3 mul`('mul' being the command for the multiplication operation).
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Calculating the expression involves understanding how stack orientation works.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Stack orientation can be presented as the following conveyor belt analogy.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] At the end of a conveyor belt (the *input*), plates marked `2`, `3`, and `mul` are placed in sequence.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The plate at the end of the conveyor (`2`) can be taken, however other plates cannot be accessed until the plate at the end is removed.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The plates can only be stored in a stack, and can only be added or removed from atop the stack, not from the middle or bottom.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Blank plates (and a marker) can be supplied and plates can be permanently discarded.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Take plate `2` and put it on the stack, then take plate `3` and put it on the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Then, take the top two plates off the stack, multiply their labels (`2` and `3`), and write the result (`6`) on a new plate.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Discard the two old plates (`2` and `3`) and the plate `mul`, and put the new plate on the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] With no more plates remaining on the conveyor, the result of the calculation (`6`) is shown on the plate atop the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] What if a more complex calculation is needed, such as `(2 + 3) × 11 + 1`?
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] If it is first written in postfix form, that is, `2 3 add 11 mul 1 add`, the calculation can be performed in exactly the same manner and achieve the correct result.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The steps of the calculation are shown in the table below.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Each column shows an input element (the plate at the end of the conveyor), and the contents of the stack after processing that input.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] After processing all the input, the stack contains `56`, which is the answer.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] From this, the following can be concluded: a stack-based programming language has only one way to handle data, by taking one piece of data from atop the stack, termed *pop*ping, and putting data back atop the stack, termed *push*ing.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Any expression that can be written *conventionally*, or in another programming language, can be written in postfix (or prefix) form and thus be amenable to being interpreted by a stack-oriented language.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Since the stack is the key means to manipulate data in a stack-oriented language, such languages often provide some sort of stack manipulation operators.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] These become key in studying procedures.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] As an aid to understanding the effect of the statement, a short comment is used showing the top of the stack before and after the statement.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The top of the stack is rightmost if there are multiple items.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] This notation is commonly used in the Forth language, where comments are enclosed in parentheses.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] It is equivalent to preconditions and postconditions in Hoare logic.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Both comments may also be referenced as assertions, though not necessarily in the context of Stack-based languages.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] PostScript and some other stack languages have other separate stacks for other purposes.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The evaluation of different expressions has already been analysed.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The implementation of variables is important for any programming language, but for stack-oriented languages, it is of special concern, as there is only one way to interact with data.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The way variables are implemented in stack-oriented languages such as PostScript usually involves a separate, specialized stack which holds *dictionaries* of key-value pairs.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] To create a variable, a key (the variable name) must be created first, with which a value is then associated.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] In PostScript, a name data object is prefixed with a `/`, so `/x` is a name data object which can be associated with, for example, the number `42`.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] associates with the name `x` with the number `42` in the dictionary atop the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] A difference exists between `/x` and `x` – the former is a data object representing a name, and `x` stands for what is defined under `/x`.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] A procedure in a stack-based programming language is treated as a data object in its own right.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] In PostScript, procedures are denoted between `{` and `}`.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] represents an anonymous procedure to duplicate what is on the top of the stack and then multiply the result – a squaring procedure.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Since procedures are treated as simple data objects, names with procedures can be defined.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] When they are retrieved, they are executed directly.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Dictionaries provide a means of controlling scoping, as well as storing definitions.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Since data objects are stored in the top-most dictionary, an unexpected ability arises naturally: when looking up a definition from a dictionary, the topmost dictionary is checked, then the next, and so on.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] If a procedure is defined that has the same name as another already defined in a different dictionary, the local one will be called.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] They are handled by the procedure in a very specific way, different from that of other programming languages.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] A recursive definition is used on the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The Fibonacci number function takes one argument.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Since the expression evaluates to true, the inner procedure is evaluated.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] This procedure does not use named variables, purely the stack.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Named variables can be created by using the `/a exch def` construct.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] is a squaring procedure with a named variable `n`.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] As there exist anonymous procedures, flow control can arise naturally.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Three pieces of data are required for an if-then-else statement: a condition, a procedure to be done if the condition is true, and one to be done if the condition is false.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] Looping and other constructs are similar.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The simple model provided in a stack-oriented language allows expressions and programs to be interpreted simply and theoretically evaluated much faster, since no syntax analysis needs to be done but lexical analysis.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] The way such programs are written facilitates being interpreted by machines, which is why PostScript suits printers well for its use.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] However, the slightly artificial way of writing PostScript programs can form an initial barrier to understanding stack-oriented languages such as PostScript.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] While the ability to shadow by overriding inbuilt and other definitions can make programs hard to debug, and irresponsible use of this feature can cause unpredictable behaviour, it can simplify some functions greatly.
[src:forth-lang/stack-oriented-programming] For example, in PostScript use, the `showpage` operator can be overridden with a custom one that applies a certain style to the page, instead of having to define a custom operator or repeat code to generate the style.
